Control loop aliasing via mechanical resonance: if a structure's natural frequency falls near or above the Nyquist frequency of a digital control loop's sampling rate, the vibration is undersampled and appears as a lower-frequency disturbance to the controller. The controller then commands corrective actuator forces at that aliased frequency, which can inject energy at the true resonant frequency, causing positive feedback and structural amplification. This is the digital implementation of the Ziegler–Nichols instability, but with the destabilizing frequency injected by sampling artifacts rather than controller gain alone. A concrete case: a reaction wheel on a spacecraft spinning at 120 Hz sampled by an attitude control loop at 100 Hz aliases to 20 Hz; the controller interprets this as a slow attitude drift and drives the wheel harder, increasing vibration amplitude until mechanical failure or saturation. Mitigation requires either anti-aliasing filters with cutoff well below Nyquist or increasing the sample rate so the resonance is fully observable and the controller's bandwidth can be shaped to roll off gain before the resonant peak.
